				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N$$\end{document} represents the population size. Second, the computational complexity of the fitness function evaluation depends on the optimization problem, and here on the objective function of the HRES optimization problem given in Eq. (1), which is of O(1)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$O(1)$$\end{document} since the objective function is a linear equation depicting the sum of the various components. Finally, the computational complexity of updating the intermediate solution is ON×M+ON×M×L\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
